english:
  title: Eulogy for the Grand Archery Ceremony
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Archery is the practice of men. From the Son of Heaven and the feudal lords down to ministers and officials, the targets differ and the musical accompaniments vary—thus are rank and station made manifest. There are ceremonies of ascent and descent, of bowing and yielding; there are melodies both graceful and harmonious—thus are ritual and music adorned. Therefore it is said: archery reveals the fullness of virtue.

    The Prime Minister of Longxi, having taken his command and gone south to garrison the region for several months, brought military affairs to excellent order. He gathered the officers and administrators and held a grand archery ceremony at the northern tower of the city. His proclamation was thus: those striking five marks shall receive from the treasury one measure of grain; those striking three shall receive half a measure. Inspectors were appointed to assess their skill. The Minister took bow and arrow to the shooting ground. With each release, his arrow flew true, providing example to the soldiers. All revered his virtue and were grateful for his recognition, each striving to display what they had learned and give their utmost effort—all that the Minister hoped and desired.

    On that day, the Bureau Director Jiang Deliang and the Colonel Zhu Fengshou both struck three marks. The others struck either two or one. When finished, the Minister seated the officers and offered them wine, music, dancing, and instrumental song—the warmth of spring breeze suffused the gathering. I am but a scholar. In archery, I can only count the scores. Yet at the feast I was honored to sit at the guest's right hand—a treasure among the assembly, by the Minister's grace. How could I remain silent and fail to celebrate this noble occasion?

    Xue Ke honored the Classics and taught propriety; Ji Zun played pitch-pot while singing the noble songs—ritual and military affairs are one path. Thus may the Minister be called a general of both culture and valor. My verses say:

    Ah, our illustrious Minister,
    In the arts of war supreme.
    When martial practice convenes,
    The pageantry gleams and gleams.
    The archers all gathered,
    Their spirits soar and glow.
    With bow and arrow in hand,
    To the cleansed ground they go.
    Many strikes mark the skillful—
    Virtue of generals great.
    The Minister takes his place,
    Spectators line the gate.
    The targets cleared away,
    He feasts in the grand hall.
    Guests sit in proper order,
    Resplendent robes adorn all.
    Ritual and music complete,
    Warm as spring's gentle sun.
    This humble scholar standing by,
    Sings praise for all that's done.
  footnotes:
    - Xue Ke and Ji Zun were celebrated exemplars from Chinese antiquity who embodied the unity of cultural refinement and military prowess—the Minister is here compared to these paragons of wisdom.
    - The grand archery ceremony (Daesha) was an important state ritual that demonstrated both virtue and martial competence, using performance in archery as a measure of moral character.
